Besides, many of the staff members had a dull Christmas as salaries had also not been paid by the time they were breaking. Despite the majority of the LSK Council having passed a resolution to have the staff paid Christmas bonuses, the society’s beleaguered president, who was not present, ‘vetoed’ the decision.
------
Water vendors frustrate residents
Just for how long will a cartel involving water company staff and water bowser owners in Buruburu continue to frustrate residents in the supply of water in their taps? In recent months, residents of Buruburu estate have not had their share of rationed water. 
Water company staff who connect the supply every Tuesday morning have not been doing so ostensibly to allow the cartel of water vendors at City Hall to sell water to the desperate residents. The water vendors have had a field day for the last four months despite several complaints by residents.
------
Official in trouble over procurement 
Back to City Hall. A top official of a State Corporation previously under the Ministry of Transport but now moved to National Treasury after a loose merger, is in trouble. 
He has, on two occasions, ignored orders from the Public Procurement Regulatory Authority over procurement issues. The Authority has now referred the matter to the big man’s board and also to Directorate of Criminal Investigations for disciplinary action and criminal prosecution, respectively. Disobeying PPRA’s orders can result to a Sh4 million fine or 20 years in prison, or both.



